WEBVTT

1
00:01:04.297 --> 00:01:06.006
What the fuck is that?

2
00:01:06.716 --> 00:01:07.883
Jimmy?

3
00:01:08.176 --> 00:01:09.927
- What's up?
- Did I hit something?

4
00:01:10.095 --> 00:01:11.762
What the fuck is that?

5
00:01:12.806 --> 00:01:14.431
Maybe you got a flat?

6
00:01:15.308 --> 00:01:17.559
Wha...? No.

7
00:01:19.187 --> 00:01:21.146
What the fuck?
You better pull over and see.

8
00:01:48.299 --> 00:01:50.551
He's still alive. You
fucking piece of shit!

9
00:01:50.719 --> 00:01:53.554
Die, you motherfucker! Look at me!

10
00:02:03.023 --> 00:02:06.984
<i>As far back as I can remember,
I always wanted to be a gangster.</i>

11
00:02:46.941 --> 00:02:47.983
<i>To me...</i>

12
00:02:48.151 --> 00:02:52.571
<i>being a gangster was better than
being president of the United States.</i>

13
00:02:55.700 --> 00:02:59.244
{\an8}<i>Even before I first wandered into
the cabstand for an after-school job...</i>

14
00:02:59.412 --> 00:03:01.497
<i>I knew I wanted to be a part of them.</i>

15
00:03:01.664 --> 00:03:04.083
<i>It was there that I knew I belonged.</i>

16
00:03:04.250 --> 00:03:08.754
<i>To me, it meant being somebody
in a neighborhood full of nobodies.</i>

17
00:03:08.922 --> 00:03:12.007
<i>They weren't like anybody else.
They did whatever they wanted.</i>

18
00:03:12.175 --> 00:03:15.761
<i>They double-parked in front of a hydrant,
nobody ever gave them a ticket.</i>

19
00:03:15.929 --> 00:03:18.263
<i>In the summer,
when they played cards all night...</i>

20
00:03:18.431 --> 00:03:20.557
<i>nobody ever called the cops.</i>

21
00:03:32.570 --> 00:03:34.613
Tony Stacks. How are you?

22
00:03:35.907 --> 00:03:37.366
<i>Tuddy Cicero.</i>

23
00:03:37.534 --> 00:03:39.827
Could this be the Canarsie Kid?

24
00:03:40.453 --> 00:03:41.995
- How are you?
- Good.

25
00:03:43.289 --> 00:03:44.456
<i>Tuddy.</i>

26
00:03:45.375 --> 00:03:48.418
<i>Tuddy ran the cabstand
and the Bella Vista Pizzeria...</i>

27
00:03:48.586 --> 00:03:53.215
<i>and other places for his brother, Paul,
who was the boss of the neighborhood.</i>

28
00:03:57.846 --> 00:04:00.139
<i>Paulie might have moved slow...</i>

29
00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:06.562
<i>but it was only because Paulie
didn't have to move for anybody.</i>

30
00:04:11.234 --> 00:04:12.860
- It's your fault.
- You started it.

31
00:04:13.027 --> 00:04:15.070
I started it? It's your fault.

32
00:04:15.238 --> 00:04:17.406
<i>At first my parents loved
that I found a job...</i>

33
00:04:17.574 --> 00:04:19.658
<i>across the street from the house.</i>

34
00:04:20.785 --> 00:04:24.538
<i>My father, who was Irish,
was sent to work at the age of 11.</i>

35
00:04:24.831 --> 00:04:26.623
<i>He liked that I got myself a job.</i>

36
00:04:26.791 --> 00:04:30.335
<i>He always used to say
that American kids were spoiled lazy.</i>

37
00:04:32.130 --> 00:04:33.755
- Bye, Dad.
- Bye.

38
00:04:34.257 --> 00:04:35.549
See you, Mikey.

39
00:04:35.717 --> 00:04:36.925
Bye, Henry.

40
00:04:37.093 --> 00:04:39.094
Henry! Watch how you cross!

41
00:04:39.262 --> 00:04:40.679
Bring back milk!

42
00:04:40.847 --> 00:04:43.974
<i>My mother was happy after
she found out that the Ciceros...</i>

43
00:04:44.142 --> 00:04:47.686
<i>came from the same part of Sicily
as she did. To my mother...</i>

44
00:04:47.854 --> 00:04:50.647
<i>that was the answer to all her prayers.</i>

45
00:04:52.108 --> 00:04:54.568
<i>I was the luckiest kid in the world.</i>

46
00:04:54.736 --> 00:04:57.571
<i>I could go anywhere, I could do anything.</i>

47
00:04:57.739 --> 00:05:00.407
<i>I knew everybody,
and everybody knew me.</i>

48
00:05:00.783 --> 00:05:03.619
<i>Wiseguys would pull up
and Tuddy would toss me their keys...</i>

49
00:05:03.786 --> 00:05:05.537
<i>and let me park their Cadillacs.</i>

50
00:05:05.705 --> 00:05:09.291
<i>Here I am, this little kid,
I can't even see over the steering wheel...</i>

51
00:05:09.459 --> 00:05:11.627
<i>and I'm parking Cadillacs.</i>

52
00:05:14.881 --> 00:05:16.965
<i>But it wasn't too long...</i>

53
00:05:17.133 --> 00:05:20.969
<i>before my parents changed
their minds about my job at the cabstand.</i>

54
00:05:21.137 --> 00:05:22.763
For your mother and sister.

55
00:05:22.931 --> 00:05:26.308
<i>For them, the cabstand was supposed
to be a part-time job. But for me...</i>

56
00:05:26.476 --> 00:05:28.435
<i>it was definitely full-time.</i>

57
00:05:28.603 --> 00:05:30.520
<i>That's all I wanted to do.</i>

58
00:05:30.688 --> 00:05:34.858
<i>People like my father could never
understand, but I was a part of something.</i>

59
00:05:35.026 --> 00:05:37.819
<i>I belonged. I was treated like a grown-up.</i>

60
00:05:38.655 --> 00:05:40.155
Tell him 519.

61
00:05:40.406 --> 00:05:42.324
<i>Every day I was learning to score.</i>

62
00:05:42.492 --> 00:05:44.993
<i>A dollar here, a dollar there.</i>

63
00:05:45.161 --> 00:05:47.079
<i>I was living in a fantasy.</i>

64
00:05:49.832 --> 00:05:51.192
Did you have a good day at school?

65
00:05:51.334 --> 00:05:53.126
<i>My father was always pissed off.</i>

66
00:05:53.294 --> 00:05:55.420
<i>Pissed that he made such lousy money...</i>

67
00:05:55.588 --> 00:05:58.507
<i>pissed that my kid brother Michael
was in a wheelchair.</i>

68
00:05:58.675 --> 00:06:02.928
<i>He was pissed that there were seven of us
living in such a tiny house.</i>

69
00:06:03.346 --> 00:06:05.055
Tell me about this.

70
00:06:05.473 --> 00:06:07.516
It's a letter from school.

71
00:06:08.017 --> 00:06:10.852
It says you haven't been there in months.

72
00:06:12.105 --> 00:06:13.438
In months!

73
00:06:15.191 --> 00:06:16.692
You're a bum!

74
00:06:16.859 --> 00:06:18.986
Want to grow up to be a bum?

75
00:06:20.530 --> 00:06:24.700
<i>After a while, he was mostly pissed
because I hung around the cabstand.</i>

76
00:06:24.867 --> 00:06:26.743
<i>He knew what went on at that cabstand.</i>

77
00:06:26.911 --> 00:06:31.540
<i>Every once in a while, I'd have to take
a beating. But by then, I didn't care.</i>

78
00:06:31.874 --> 00:06:33.583
<i>The way I saw it...</i>

79
00:06:33.918 --> 00:06:36.545
<i>everybody takes a beating sometime.</i>

80
00:06:37.755 --> 00:06:41.508
- I can't make any more deliveries.
- What? You'll fuck everything up.

81
00:06:41.676 --> 00:06:43.719
My dad says he'll kill me. Look.

82
00:06:43.886 --> 00:06:45.345
Come on with me.

83
00:06:45.596 --> 00:06:47.514
- Is that him, kid?
- No.

84
00:06:48.182 --> 00:06:49.891
- How about him?
- No.

85
00:06:51.894 --> 00:06:53.937
- That's the guy.
- Get him.

86
00:06:55.732 --> 00:06:57.065
Excuse me.

87
00:06:58.234 --> 00:07:00.902
- Scumbag.
- Come here, you piece of shit.

88
00:07:08.703 --> 00:07:10.829
- Know this kid?
- Yeah.

89
00:07:10.997 --> 00:07:12.581
- Know where he lives?
- Yeah.

90
00:07:12.749 --> 00:07:14.958
- You deliver mail to his house?
- Yeah.

91
00:07:15.126 --> 00:07:18.920
From now on, any letter from that
school to his house comes directly here.

92
00:07:19.088 --> 00:07:20.172
- Understand?
- Yeah.

93
00:07:20.340 --> 00:07:23.050
Another letter from that school
goes to that kid's house...

94
00:07:23.217 --> 00:07:25.719
in the fucking oven you'll go, head first.

95
00:07:25.887 --> 00:07:30.182
<i>That was it. No more letters from
truant officers. No letters from school.</i>

96
00:07:30.350 --> 00:07:32.434
<i>In fact, no more letters from anybody.</i>

97
00:07:32.602 --> 00:07:36.396
<i>Finally after a few weeks, my mother
went to the post office to complain.</i>

98
00:07:36.939 --> 00:07:38.459
<i>How could I go to school after that...</i>

99
00:07:38.566 --> 00:07:42.694
<i>and pledge allegiance to the flag
and sit through good government bullshit?</i>

100
00:07:45.782 --> 00:07:48.950
<i>Paulie hated phones.
He wouldn't have one in his house.</i>

101
00:07:49.118 --> 00:07:51.787
Mickey called. Want me to call him back?

102
00:07:52.163 --> 00:07:53.789
All right, make the call.

103
00:07:53.956 --> 00:07:57.542
<i>He got all his calls second hand.
Then you'd have to call the people back...</i>

104
00:07:57.710 --> 00:07:58.752
<i>from an outside phone.</i>

105
00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:01.380
Got a nickel? Get him on the phone.

106
00:08:02.131 --> 00:08:06.885
<i>There were guys, that's all they did
all day, was take care of Paulie's calls.</i>

107
00:08:16.521 --> 00:08:20.816
<i>For a guy who moved all day long,
Paulie didn't talk to six people.</i>

108
00:08:20.983 --> 00:08:23.985
<i>If there was a union problem
or, say, a beef in the numbers...</i>

109
00:08:24.153 --> 00:08:27.656
<i>only the top guys could meet
with Paulie to discuss the problem.</i>

110
00:08:27.824 --> 00:08:31.076
<i>Everything was one-on-one.
Paulie hated conferences.</i>

111
00:08:31.828 --> 00:08:34.287
<i>He didn't want anybody
hearing what he said...</i>

112
00:08:34.455 --> 00:08:37.749
<i>and he didn't want anybody listening
to what he was being told.</i>

113
00:08:37.917 --> 00:08:42.170
<i>Hundreds of guys depended on Paulie,
he got a piece of everything they made.</i>

114
00:08:42.338 --> 00:08:46.675
<i>It was a tribute, like in the old country,
except they were doing it in America.</i>

115
00:08:46.843 --> 00:08:51.304
<i>All they got from Paulie was protection
from other guys looking to rip them off.</i>

116
00:08:51.472 --> 00:08:55.392
<i>That's what it's all about. That's what
the FBI could never understand.</i>

117
00:08:55.852 --> 00:08:58.019
<i>What Paulie and the Organization does...</i>

118
00:08:58.187 --> 00:09:02.107
<i>is offer protection for people
who can't go to the cops. That's it.</i>

119
00:09:02.692 --> 00:09:06.820
<i>That's all it is. They're like
the police department for wiseguys.</i>

120
00:09:16.622 --> 00:09:20.709
<i>People looked at me differently,
and they knew I was with somebody.</i>

121
00:09:20.877 --> 00:09:25.213
<i>I didn't have to wait in line at the bakery
on Sunday mornings for fresh bread.</i>

122
00:09:25.381 --> 00:09:26.756
<i>The owner knew who I was with...</i>

123
00:09:26.924 --> 00:09:30.302
<i>and he'd come from around the counter.
No matter how many were waiting...</i>

124
00:09:30.470 --> 00:09:32.471
<i>I was taken care of first.</i>

125
00:09:32.722 --> 00:09:35.056
<i>Our neighbors didn't park
in our driveway anymore...</i>

126
00:09:35.224 --> 00:09:37.851
<i>even though we didn't have a car.
At 13...</i>

127
00:09:38.019 --> 00:09:40.896
<i>I was making more money than most
of the grown-ups around.</i>

128
00:09:41.063 --> 00:09:44.191
<i>I had more money than I could spend.
I had it all.</i>

129
00:09:54.327 --> 00:09:58.997
<i>One day, some neighborhood kids carried
my mother's groceries all the way home.</i>

130
00:09:59.165 --> 00:10:00.582
<i>You know why?</i>

131
00:10:01.417 --> 00:10:03.251
<i>It was out of respect.</i>

132
00:10:05.004 --> 00:10:07.088
Hi, Mom, what do you think?

133
00:10:08.716 --> 00:10:11.426
- Look at my shoes, aren't they great?
- My God.

134
00:10:11.969 --> 00:10:13.553
You look like a gangster.

135
00:10:13.721 --> 00:10:15.430
They shot me. Help!

136
00:10:18.059 --> 00:10:19.851
Henry, shut the door.

137
00:10:20.853 --> 00:10:24.147
<i>That was the first time
I had ever seen anyone shot.</i>

138
00:10:24.941 --> 00:10:27.108
Can't have that in here. Jesus Christ!

139
00:10:27.276 --> 00:10:29.194
I can't have that in this joint.

140
00:10:29.362 --> 00:10:31.112
<i>I remember feeling bad about the guy...</i>

141
00:10:31.280 --> 00:10:34.407
<i>but I also remember feeling
that maybe Tuddy was right.</i>

142
00:10:34.659 --> 00:10:37.285
<i>I knew Paulie didn't want
anybody dying in the building.</i>

143
00:10:37.453 --> 00:10:41.289
You're a real jerk. You wasted
eight fucking aprons on this guy.

144
00:10:41.457 --> 00:10:44.709
What the hell's wrong with you?
I got to toughen this kid up.

145
00:11:04.397 --> 00:11:06.314
<i>It was a glorious time.</i>

146
00:11:07.233 --> 00:11:09.818
<i>And wiseguys were all over the place.</i>

147
00:11:10.778 --> 00:11:13.738
<i>It was before Apalachin
and before Crazy Joe...</i>

148
00:11:13.906 --> 00:11:16.825
<i>decided to take on a boss and start a war.</i>

149
00:11:17.493 --> 00:11:19.536
<i>It was when I met the world.</i>

150
00:11:19.704 --> 00:11:22.414
<i>And it was when I first met
Jimmy Conway.</i>

151
00:11:23.666 --> 00:11:27.043
<i>He couldn't have been more than 28 or 29
at the time...</i>

152
00:11:27.211 --> 00:11:29.129
<i>but he was already a legend.</i>

153
00:11:29.297 --> 00:11:33.300
<i>He'd walk in the door and everybody
who worked the room just went wild.</i>

154
00:11:33.467 --> 00:11:36.052
<i>He'd give the doorman $100
just for opening the door.</i>

155
00:11:36.220 --> 00:11:40.140
<i>He'd give hundreds to the dealers
and the guys who ran the games.</i>

156
00:11:40.308 --> 00:11:43.268
<i>The bartender got $100
just for keeping the ice cubes cold.</i>

157
00:11:43.436 --> 00:11:46.521
The Irishman is here
to take all you guineas' money.

158
00:11:49.734 --> 00:11:52.485
- Want a drink?
- Give me a 7 and 7.

159
00:11:59.619 --> 00:12:02.996
- I'd like you to meet the kid Henry.
- How you doing?

160
00:12:05.374 --> 00:12:08.084
- Thank you.
- Keep them coming.

161
00:12:08.252 --> 00:12:11.254
<i>Jimmy was one of the most
feared guys in the city.</i>

162
00:12:11.422 --> 00:12:13.048
<i>He was first locked up at 11...</i>

163
00:12:13.215 --> 00:12:16.301
<i>and he was doing hits
for mob bosses when he was 16.</i>

164
00:12:16.469 --> 00:12:19.262
<i>See, hits never bothered Jimmy.
It was business.</i>

165
00:12:19.722 --> 00:12:21.806
<i>But what Jimmy really loved to do...</i>

166
00:12:21.974 --> 00:12:23.975
<i>what he really loved to do was steal.</i>

167
00:12:24.143 --> 00:12:26.353
<i>He actually enjoyed it.</i>

168
00:12:26.520 --> 00:12:30.440
<i>Jimmy was the kind of guy who rooted
for the bad guys in the movies.</i>

169
00:12:31.150 --> 00:12:32.901
Give me your wallet.

170
00:12:35.905 --> 00:12:39.032
You might know who we are,
but we know who you are. Understand?

171
00:12:39.200 --> 00:12:41.618
<i>He was one of
the city's biggest hijackers...</i>

172
00:12:41.786 --> 00:12:45.372
<i>of booze, cigarettes, razor blades,
shrimp and lobsters.</i>

173
00:12:45.539 --> 00:12:48.458
<i>Shrimp and lobsters were best.
They went really fast.</i>

174
00:12:48.626 --> 00:12:52.504
<i>Almost all of them were gimmies.
They just gave it up, no problem.</i>

175
00:12:52.672 --> 00:12:54.339
<i>They called him Jimmy the Gent.</i>

176
00:12:54.507 --> 00:12:55.632
Help the lady.

177
00:12:55.800 --> 00:12:57.884
<i>Drivers loved him.
They used to tip him off...</i>

178
00:12:58.052 --> 00:13:01.596
<i>about the really good loads.
Of course, everybody got a piece.</i>

179
00:13:01.764 --> 00:13:03.848
Thanks, I'll be back for the rest later.

180
00:13:04.016 --> 00:13:05.433
Okay, see you later.

181
00:13:07.978 --> 00:13:09.604
Henry, come here.

182
00:13:10.523 --> 00:13:12.565
- Say hello to Tommy.
- How're you doing, Henry?

183
00:13:12.733 --> 00:13:14.734
You're gonna be working together, okay?

184
00:13:14.902 --> 00:13:16.611
Help him. Go ahead.

185
00:13:16.987 --> 00:13:19.114
Jimmy, you got anything good?

186
00:13:19.281 --> 00:13:23.493
<i>And when the cops assigned a
whole army to stop Jimmy, what did he do?</i>

187
00:13:23.661 --> 00:13:24.661
How're you doing?

188
00:13:24.829 --> 00:13:26.579
<i>He made them partners.</i>

189
00:13:26.747 --> 00:13:28.456
I'd complain, but who'd listen?

190
00:13:28.958 --> 00:13:30.291
- One Pall Mall.
- There you go.

191
00:13:30.459 --> 00:13:32.585
- What do you need?
- Two Luckies.

192
00:13:32.753 --> 00:13:34.629
- Here you go, Henry.
- Thanks a lot.

193
00:13:34.797 --> 00:13:35.797
What do you need?

194
00:13:35.965 --> 00:13:38.633
- One Pall Mall.
- One Pall Mall, here you go.

195
00:13:38.801 --> 00:13:40.468
- What are you doing?
- It's all right.

196
00:13:40.636 --> 00:13:43.638
- You have permission from your mother?
- How many cartons you need?

197
00:13:43.806 --> 00:13:46.850
- Where'd you get the cigarettes?
- Get him out of here.

198
00:13:47.017 --> 00:13:48.768
- It's okay.
- It's not okay.

199
00:13:48.936 --> 00:13:52.188
- You don't understand.
- You don't understand. Store's closed.

200
00:13:57.027 --> 00:13:58.862
- Henry got pinched.
- Where?

201
00:13:59.029 --> 00:14:00.822
By the factory, selling cigarettes.

202
00:14:00.990 --> 00:14:04.826
<i>Henry Hill. The People of
the State of New York vs. Henry Hill.</i>

203
00:14:05.119 --> 00:14:07.912
Docket number 704162.

204
00:14:08.998 --> 00:14:11.291
Uh, yes, sir. That's me.

205
00:14:14.086 --> 00:14:16.838
Just stand there. Now stay there.

206
00:14:23.262 --> 00:14:25.013
Counselor, proceed.

207
00:14:28.017 --> 00:14:29.642
Congratulations.

208
00:14:29.935 --> 00:14:31.853
Here's your graduation present.

209
00:14:32.021 --> 00:14:34.981
- What for? I got pinched.
- Everyone does, but you did it right.

210
00:14:35.149 --> 00:14:37.192
You told them nothing,
and they got nothing.

211
00:14:37.359 --> 00:14:40.528
- I thought you'd be mad.
- I'm not mad, I'm proud of you.

212
00:14:40.696 --> 00:14:44.991
You took your first pinch like a man and
learned the two greatest things in life.

213
00:14:45.159 --> 00:14:47.494
- What?
- Look at me.

214
00:14:48.204 --> 00:14:50.330
Never rat on your friends...

215
00:14:50.498 --> 00:14:52.832
and always keep your mouth shut.

216
00:14:55.920 --> 00:14:57.295
Here he is.

217
00:14:57.838 --> 00:14:59.714
You broke your cherry.

218
00:15:06.764 --> 00:15:08.389
Congratulations!

219
00:15:43.092 --> 00:15:46.344
<i>By the time I grew up,
there was $30 billion a year in cargo...</i>

220
00:15:46.512 --> 00:15:48.263
